<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11120e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11120e">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11120e"> 120(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cynisme des chiens / chouette, tombaient palpitantes / bless&eacute;es &amp; fatidiques / les infirmit&eacute;s de l&apos;ame / et du corps ont jou&eacute; / un grand r&ocirc;le dans / n<font color="green">[os]</font> troubles</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Aux Cordeliers: Marat et ses amis</b> Les gestes rendaient les images sensibles; tout &eacute;tait appel&eacute; par son nom, avec <mark>le cynsime des chiens</mark>, dans une pompe obscene et impie de jurements et de blasph&egrave;mes. D&eacute;truire e produire, mort et g&eacute;n&eacute;ration, on ne d&eacute;m&eacute;lait que cela &agrave; travers l&apos;argot sauvage dont les oreilles &eacute;taient assourdies. Les harangueurs, &agrave; la voix gr&ecirc;le ou tonnante, avaient d&apos;autres interrupteurs que leurs opposants: les petites <mark>chouettes</mark> noire du clo&icirc;tre sans moines et du clocher sans cloches, s&apos;&eacute;jouissaient aux fen&ecirc;tres bris&eacute;es, en espoir du butin; elles interrompaient les discours. On les rappelait d&apos;abord &agrave; l&apos;ordre par le tintamarre de l&apos;impuissante sonnette; mais ne cessant point leur criaillement, on leur tirait des coups de fusil pour leur faire silence: elles <mark>tombaient; palpitantes, bless&eacute;es et fatidiques</mark>, au milieu du Pand&eacute;monium. Des charpentes abattues, des bancs boiteux, des stalles d&eacute;mantibul&eacute;es, des tron&ccedil;ons de saints roul&eacute;s et pouss&eacute;s contre les murs, servaient de gradins aux spectateurs crott&eacute;s, poudreux, so&ucirc;ls, suants, en carmagnole perc&eacute;e, la pique sur l&apos;&eacute;paule ou les bras nus crois&eacute;s. Les plus difformes de la bande obtenaient de pr&eacute;f&eacute;rence la parole. <mark>Les infirmit&eacute;s de l&apos;&acirc;me et du corps ont jou&eacute; un r&ocirc;le dans nos troubles</mark>: l&apos;amour-propre en souffrance a fait de grands r&eacute;volutionnaires. <br><font color="green">[At the Cordeliers: Marat and his friends: Images were made tangible through gestures; everything was called by its name, with the cynicism of dogs, with an obscene and impious display of oaths and blasphemies. Destruction and productivity, death and generation: one could only disentangle them through that wild jargon which deafened one&apos;s ears. Orators, in shrill or thunderous voices, had other interrupters besides their opponents: little black screech-owls from monkless cloisters and belfries without bells, revelled by the broken windows in the hope of booty&mdash;they interrupted the speeches. They were recalled to order by the tinkling of an ineffectual handbell, but they scarcely ceased their bawling. Rifle shots were fired at them to shut them up; they fell, trembling, wounded and fatidic in the midst of the pandemonium. Broken down timbers, rickety benches, smashed stalls, broken bits of saints, rolled and pushed against the walls served as seating for the dusty, drunk and sweaty spectators in pierced carmagnoles, with pike on shoulder or naked crossed arms. The most malformed of the gang got preference in speaking. Infirmities of soul and body played a role in our unrest: self-esteem in abeyance made great revolutionaries.]</font> <small> Chateaubriand, <a name="CHBD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CHBD"><cite title="source">&OElig;uvres choisies illustr&eacute;es</cite></a> (1912) III, <i> M&eacute;moires d&apos;Outre-tombe.</i> 70</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
